description:
New sprite.{h,cpp} + sprite.glsl. API:
  void SpriteRenderer::init();
  void SpriteRenderer::destroy();
  void SpriteRenderer::draw(const std::vector<SpriteObject>& objs, const Camera& cam);

Two draw passes per frame:
  (1) HULL pass — alpha-blended textured quads, depth test ON, depth write ON, back-to-front sort. Non-premultiplied alpha.
  (2) LIGHTS pass — additive-blended textured quads + the animated light spots, depth test ON, depth write OFF. Quads share the same billboard geometry as hulls.

Vertex shader computes camera-facing quad from the object's world position + per-vertex corner offset. Fragment shader samples hull_tex (for hull pass) or lights_tex + procedural spots (for lights pass). Anim spots drawn as a SECOND additive pass on top of the lights texture, blink_hz driven by time uniform.

Keep under 400 LOC, single file. If animated-spot logic grows, factor later.

Extend system JSON with a 'placed_sprites' array parallel to placed_meshes:

  "placed_sprites": [
    {
      "sprite":       "sprites/mining_base",
      "position":     [1500, 400, 25500],
      "length_meters":1200,
      "lights": [
        { "u": 0.72, "v": 0.40, "color": [255,30,30], "size": 20, "blink_hz": 1.0, "kind": "strobe" },
        ...
      ]
    }
  ]

Loader resolves sprite to <sprite>.png + <sprite>_lights.png. length_meters drives the billboard's world size (analogous to mesh length). Animated lights are authored per-object in the system JSON so different stations can have distinct blinking personalities.

The painted lights layer is static. The JUICE comes from animated spots:

  struct LightSpot {
    float u, v;             // UV on the sprite [0..1]
    uint32_t rgba;          // tint + base intensity
    float size;             // world-space radius
    float blink_hz;         // 0 = steady, 1.5 = slow heartbeat, 10 = strobe
    float phase;            // 0..1, staggers multiple spots
    enum Kind { PULSE, STROBE, STEADY } kind;
  };

Per-frame in sprite.glsl lights pass:
  intensity = (kind==STROBE)  ? step(0.5, fract(t*blink_hz + phase))
            : (kind==PULSE)   ? 0.5 + 0.5*sin(t*blink_hz*6.283 + phase*6.283)
            :                    1.0;
  out = base_rgba * intensity;

Quads are tiny (size world units), drawn additively, with a soft radial falloff in the fragment shader (smoothstep from center). Acts as in-bloom point light without needing a real light source.
